I just wrote :

> I would certainly, however, agree that it's not possible to amend one
> Order into more than one. Generally, in fact, I think we'll need to
> give 'amend' a commonsensical interpretation; amending an Order
> means altering some particulars of it, e.g. changing the amount,
> the Currency or the payee in a Transfer Order; but I'm not certain
> it should even be possible to amend an existing Order to apply to
> a different Player than it applied to originally

Hmm. I take that back. If we interpret Orders as being non-Rule
bodies of text with coercive power granted by Rules 1810 and 1811,
as it still seems logical to me to do, then amending such bodies of
text in the same manner that we amend Rules makes sense.

The problematic notion here is that of 'one' Order. The problem is
that there is no clear 'granularity', so to speak, which could let
us count Orders. Suppose I posted a message saying "Swann is
hereby commanded to give 1 VT to an English-speaking Player,
and to give 1 VT to a Player living in the US", how many Orders
should we count ? Two, because there are two sets identified,
or only one, because Swann could comply with this Order by
carrying out only one action (giving a VT to an English-speaking
Player living in the US) ?

Thus, what Swann did was more akin to amending one Rule to
contain two clauses when it originally contained one. So I would
probably rule that Macross' objection doesn't apply.


