The good General made a similar remark a while ago. I initially
agreed, but that interpretation clashes with my notion that Orders
are no more nor less than bodies of text with coercive power (i.e.
the equivalent of Subordinate Legal Codes). Under that interpretation,
there's no problem with multiplying "Orders" by amendment - youre'
only adding more clauses to a text which previously covered fewer
cases.

I'm still not sure whether that is a fatal flaw with the "Orders as
SLCs" principle or an indication of its usefulness. ;) But as I've 
remarked, an argument based on the principle that Orders can
be somehow counted might get dangerously close to angels-on-
a-pinhead issues.


