I see a number of possible interpretations in decreasing order of
probability;
(Invalidity here refers to an Order that would be properly adjudicated
invalid eventually)

1) The amendment caused a split of One Order into two, and both orders
were valid because the amendment creating the second Order was
permissible.

2) The amendment caused a split of one Order into two, and the latter
Order, the appended text that was amended, is invalid because the
amended was a de-facto issuing of a new arbitrary Order, which was
forbidden.

3) The amendment didn't cause a split, but created a new, improperly
formed Order which would be adjudicated invalid.

4) The amendment didn't cause a split, and the Order is still valid
because 1783 explicitly grants power for 1800 to allow amendments, and
the amended Order, to be effective even when the amendment contradicts
the provisions of 1793.

5) The amendment made the Order into something that isn't an Order.

5.1) The above, and the amendment itself was invalid because of that
fact.

6) The amendment itself wasn't properly formed, and therefore wasn't an
Order, and never changed anything.

The first three I find the most likely interpretations, the latter four
I find to be somewhat unlikely or "weird" but possible alternate
interpretations.

Swann



