> I believe the question is whether the act of amending a single order
> can "bifurcate" that order into two orders.  That's the situation
> which exists here.  If we take your interpretation (which seems
> logical), then the actual effect of Swann's amending order was to (a)
> amend one order and (b) execute a new order.  Unless I've missed
> something, (b) was prohibited.  It becomes an exercise in sophistry to
> decide which of the two resulting orders is the improperly executed
> one, however.
>

Rule 1800/0 reads in part:

"
Amendment of Orders

      The effect of amending an Order is to cause it to be effective
      in its amended form.  The prior form of the Order ceases to have
      effect upon the amendment, and the new form has effect as if it
      had been originally executed in that form at the moment the
      amendment becomes effective.
"

This is the only place in the Rules that I can find mention of
the effects of amending an Order and I don't think this would
allow amended Orders to bifurcate.  I am of course open to argument
to the contrary.

-Macross

