>       An Order is a command, executed by a Player and directed to some
>       entity requiring that entity to perform exactly one action, or
>       to refrain from performing one or more actions.
> 
> If it commands someone to both perform and not to perform actions, or to
> perform more than one action, it is not an Order.

 Confusion of levels here. In the same *sentence* (or for that matter
in the same phrase) you might very well find more than one 'command'
(in the standard english meaning of the term, synonymous to
injunction, entreaty, etc.). But the Rules don't require that an
Order be a full sentence (and no more). Examples : "Oerjan, shut up
and stop contradicting me" is a sentence with two commands; "Swann,
please vacate one of the Orders you've issued. I'm referring
specifically to the last Order in your message 'Here we go'" is one
single command in two sentences.

 Short of a logical contradiction, therefore (e.g. "Morendil, will 
you please make yourself clear by not writing anything more on
the subject") you will have a very hard time finding a single Order 
that both requires an action and prohibits an action.

 The Rule fragment you quote above is confusing because of the 
tension between "exactly one" and "one or more" - suggesting that 
Orders are something you can count with precision - but in my
opinion that's simply not the case.

 We do on the other hand have some game custom to the effect that if
one writes "I hereby issue _one_ Order requiring Player X to do Y",
then that should count as one Order. (I'm reasoning by analogy to the
occasion when I was brought to court for issuing, as Judge, illegal 
Injunctions and it was ruled that a Player stating "I hereby issue 
many Injunctions" was presumed to have issued more than one. The 
situation here is not quite analogous, but somewhat similar.) But as
far as I can see Swann was not using this kind of phrasing; merely 
stating "I hereby Order X to doY, Z, and W".


