>      An Order shall be invalidated upon its execution if any of the 
>      following is true of it;
> 
>        i) It seeks to hinder the appeal of itself or some other Order
>       ii) It seeks to hinder the stay, vacation or amendment of itself 
>           or another Order.

Not good. A Court of Appeals needs to be able to reverse a Judge's 
incorrectly issued Order to Stay or Vacate another Order.

>      iii) The Order itself is in direct violation of one or more Rules.
>       iv) It seeks to compel, or forbid, the performance of any duty
>           required or permitted of a Player solely by the virtue of that
>           Player being a Judge or Justice.
>        v) It seeks to forbid any Player from submitting a CFJ, appealing
>           a CFJ, or submitting a Motion.

I'd replace v) by something much stronger, such as "v) it seeks to 
deprive a Player of a right granted em by the Rules, in the absence 
of explicit provisions in the Rules for an Order with such effects".

This will both preserve the Rules' ultimate power, as well as let us
rewrite something like Orders to suspend Voting privileges more
naturally : "The Assessor may deprive a Player of eir Voting
privilege by issuing an Order to refrain from Voting on Proposals
for a period not exceeding X weeks".

On the other hand, I'd be even more in favor of making the notion
of "Orders as non-Rule entities with coercive power" explicit, which
would make a lot of the foregoing unnecessary, as well as some
of what follows.

> Let the following Rule be created with a Power=2;
> (Title: Precedence of Orders)

This could be tied in with 'Orders as NREs' simply by having one
Rule for each class, explicitly stating that "Orders of class X have
coercive power over Players; this Rule takes precedence over any
Rule granting coercive power to Orders of class Y but defers to any
Rule granting coercive power to Orders of class Z and W".

>      An Order can only affect the operation of another Order when the 
>      Order so affected does not take precedence over it.  An Order that
>      attempts to do so is invalidated upon execution.

This (plus an implied 'unless the Rules specify otherwise') would 
directly follow from "Orders as NREs".

>       All Administrative, Judicial, and Appellate Orders executed in the
>       manner prescribed by the Rules for their class and type are 
>       presumed valid and enforceable until proven otherwise by CFJ.

Let's drop this "type" language altogether. Let all such orders be
presumed valid.

>        i) Private Orders shall not be for a proper purpose unless they 
>           are directly relevant to the personal business of the Player 
>           issuing them, or to the business of entities over which that 
>           player has legal control when the Order was issued.
>       ii) Administrative Orders shall not be for a proper purpose unless 
>           they are directly relevant to the performance of the official 
>           duties of the Player issuing them.
>      iii) Judicial Orders shall not be for a proper purpose unless they 
>           are directly relevant to a CFJ being Judged by the Player 
>           issuing them.
>       iv) Appellate Orders shall not be for a proper purpose unless they 
>           are directly relevant to an issue that Board is currently 
>           adjudicating.

That's good... Perhaps i) needs some fine-tuning; something along
the lines of "are directly relevant to an agreement entered into by
the Player issuing the Order and the Player or Players to whom the
Order is directed", which would form a good basis for adjudicting
contract disputes.


